+**The autouse-`default_workers` trap (must be handled, or the "off the base
+path" claim is false).** `default_workers`
+([`plugin.py`](../../conformance/src/conformance/harness/plugin.py) ~L257) is an
+**autouse** fixture that depends on `wire_client` → `iut`. Autouse means *every*
+test function pulls it in — so a durability test that only requests
+`durable_clients` would *still* spin up the base `iut` + `wire_client` +
+control-plane subprocess (unused, wasteful, and a second IUT racing the durable
+one), and the "plugin.py untouched / off the shared path" claim would be false.
+The fix is a **module-level autouse override** in
+`test_experiment_durability.py`: redefine `default_workers` as an autouse no-op
+that does **not** depend on `wire_client` (the `durable_clients` fixture does all
+worker seeding on its own client). A same-name fixture defined at module scope
+shadows the plugin's definition for that module only; because the override does
+not request `wire_client`, the base `iut`/`wire_client`/control-plane chain is
+never instantiated for durability tests. This keeps `plugin.py` genuinely
+untouched and the durability path genuinely off the shared base fixtures. (The
+override must itself be `autouse=True` so it actually replaces the plugin's
+autouse fixture in that module; a non-autouse same-name fixture would leave the
+plugin's autouse one in effect.) Confirm in validation that a durability test run
+spawns exactly one IUT per test (no stray base IUT) — e.g. assert via process
+count or a logging probe during the wave-1 smoke.
 
